The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Nation | Rail exam off after leak
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                     Rail exam off after leak
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                          Examinees detained in Allahabad on Sunday. (PTI)                                  
	Lucknow, Dec. 14: Several Railway Recruitment Board exams to be held today were cancelled after Uttar Pradesh police claimed to have busted a gang, allegedly led by a travelling ticket examiner, that leaked question papers.         
	The special task force of the police raided an exam centre outside Allahabad hours before the tests were to begin and arrested 11 people.        
	The question papers were kept at this exam centre, from where they were to be distributed to 39 other centres this morning. A Railway Recruitment Board office is located nearby.         
	Bedi Lal, the alleged kingpin, was arrested from a building near the exam centre while he was photocopying answers to the questions. Ten others were caught selling the questions and answers.        
	Surya Kumar, inspector-general of police, Allahabad zone, said the police first picked up the 11, seizing money and papers from them, then rounded up over 270 candidates who had already bought the leaked question papers.        
	Lal, a ticket examiner, worked for the North Eastern Railway that is headquartered in Gonda, about 200km from Lucknow, the police said.        
	 He had been arrested in 2006 in another railway question paper leak case but was freed on bail.         
	Additional director-general of police Brij Lal said the 11  six are rail employees  taken into custody had named others involved in the racket. The papers were being sold for anything between Rs 1 lakh and 2 lakh, he said.         
	Among the detained candidates, 139 were from Bihar, 100 from Uttar Pradesh, 23 Rajasthan, seven Jharkhand and one each from Chhattisgarh, Orissa, Madhya Pradesh, Uttarakhand and Bengal, Brij Lal said.        
	Over 37,000 candidates had arrived in Allahabad to sit for the exams for the posts of assistant loco driver, loco driver and assistant radio pilot, among others. The police suspect that the paper for each post was leaked.                                                                                                                                                                          
